title: narusegawa_naru
body:
One of the central characters of the [[Love Hina]] series, she is a 17-year old high school student at the start of the series and a resident of the Hinata Inn (ex-inn turned girls' dormitory). She aims to get accepted to Tokyo University and spends most of her spare time doing heavy studying to achieve this goal.

A model of the [[tsundere]] archetype, she has a fiery temper and a tendency to inflict violent physical punishment to the main protaganist [[Urashima Keitarou]].  Despite her violent tendencies, she also has a very caring side and has been shown encouraging and caring for many of the other characters over the course of the series.

While her family is barely mentioned in the series, she has a younger half-sister named [[Narusegawa Mei]] who makes an appearance in the anime and the epilogue chapter of the manga.

title: cymothoa_exigua
body:
Also known as the tongue-eating louse; it is a species of parasitic [[isopod]] [[crustacean]] whose females attach themselves to a fish host's tongue and feed on blood. Eventually the tongue is reduced to a stub and the [[parasite]] effectively becomes the fish's new tongue.
The Cymothoidae family is incorrectly called [i]uonoe[/i] (lit. "fish-food") in Japanese. (And its subspecies are called [i]tainoe[/i] (bream-food), [i]fugunoe[/i] (puffer-fish-food) and [i]tobiuonoe[/i] (flying-fish-food))

h4.See also:

title: blueberry_inflation
body:
A genre of expansionism, blueberry expansion is a fantasy fetish in which a female (and less commonly a male) turns blue, fills up with blueberry juice until they become spherical, and basically transforms into a human blueberry.

Blueberry fetishism draws its roots from the 1971 film Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory, where the character Violet Beauregarde transforms into a giant blueberry after chewing a fantastical piece of gum which contains a full three-course meal - the problem being in the dessert, with the blueberry pie.

body:
Also known as hiropon or shabu. The brand-name methamphetamine sold by Dainippon Pharmaceuticals for civilian and military use. (At the time, the side effects of methamphetamine were not well studied.)
After [[World War II]] a large military stockpile of Philopon flooded the market. The Japanese government banned it in 1951.

title: tanabe_kozue
body:
[b]Series:[/b] [[Shinryaku!_Ikamusume|Shinryaku! Ika Musume]]

A mysterious character who's appeared only once (twice in the anime). When Ika Musume was down in the dumps about the course of the "invasion", Kozue encouraged her to see value in her experiences regardless -- and cryptically told her she wasn't alone. 

The initials of [b]Ta[/b]nabe [b]Ko[/b]zue spell "octopus" in Japanese, and she wears a hat that looks suspiciously like an octopus's head, just like Ika's hat resembles a squid's. Fans have therefore dubbed her [b]Tako-Musume[/b] (Octopus Girl).

title: saitou_nagisa
body:
[b]Series:[/b] [[Shinryaku!_Ikamusume|Shinryaku! Ika Musume]]

The one and only character who takes Ika Musume at her word. Nagisa got a job at the Aizawa family's beachhouse and was horrified to find a squid monster waiting tables. She finds Ika creepy rather than cute, and thinks her invasion plans are scary rather than harmless bluster. (Naturally, this thrills Ika to no end.) Eventually, as Nagisa discovers how ordinary Ika is most of the time, she perversely finds herself getting excited any time the "fearsome invader" puts in a little effort.

Nagisa has [[short hair]], is into [[surfing]] (for which she wears a [[wetsuit]]), and is generally a tomboy -- to the point where she can pass for a guy with just a few slight adjustments. [[Aizawa Eiko|Eiko]] sometimes makes her do this in an attempt to bring in more female customers, and to Nagisa's dismay, it works [i]really[/i] well.

Of course, both Kirishima and Yotarou's tags can also be used together if both the two appear together in a single scene or if Kirishima emerges from some sort of "[[bear costume|Yotarou costume]]."

title: wilhelmina_carmel
body:
[b]Series:[/b] [[Shakugan no Shana]]
[b]Title:[/b] Manipulator of Objects

The Flame Haze bound to the Crimson Lord Tiamat. Wilhelmina is [[Shana]]'s adoptive mother (though neither of them uses the word), having rescued her as an infant and raised her. She has the appearance of a woman in her 20s, but is clearly much older; she seems to have a past with every new character who turns up. She's also one of the most skilled and powerful fighters in the series -- bad news for anyone who gets close to Shana, of whom she's [i]very[/i] protective.

Wilhelmina is something of an oddball. As the servant of a Crimson God (Alastor, the one bound to Shana), she's highly aristocratic, ending her sentences with [i]de arimasu[/i] (an old-fashioned, formal variant of [i]desu[/i]) and wearing a [[maid]] outfit at all times. She speaks in monotone and has facial expressions to match; it takes a lot to make her smile. Nonetheless, her emotions run deep and she forms strong bonds with those who fight beside her. 

Almost all pictures of Wilhelmina include Tiamat, who's housed in her [[maid headdress|frilly maid thing]], and therefore has no separate tag.

Marchosias is the Crimson Lord who lends his power to [[Margery Daw]]. He talks to her through the big book she carries (called Grimoire). title: margery_daw
body:
[b]Series:[/b] [[Shakugan no Shana]]
[b]Title:[/b] Interpreter of Condolences / Chanter of Elegies

The Flame Haze bound to the Crimson Lord [[Marchosias]]. Margery is a hard-drinking brawler who lives to kill Crimson Denizens -- and is very good at it. Her ultimate goal is vengeance on an entity called the Silver, but she's got plenty of rage to go around, as [[Shana]] finds out early on. Upon arriving in Misaki City, Margery randomly enlists [[Satou Keisaku]] and [[Tanaka Eita]] as assistants; she soon becomes fond of them, and learns to get along with Shana, but it's a long time before she really opens up to anyone.

Margery wears [[glasses]], a [[ponytail]], and a [[choker]], and dresses like an [[office lady]]. The big book she's usually carrying is the vessel of Marchosias (whom she yells at a lot). Her name comes from an old nursery rhyme; this theme carries over to her attacks, which involve reciting a line or two of poetry. She can also turn into a werewolf, of all things.

title: murder_princess
body:
A two-volume manga (2005-7) and six-episode OVA (2008, by Studio BEE TRAIN of Noir/Madlax fame).

When Princess [[Alita Forland]] flees her castle to escape a military coup, she bashes heads with the bounty hunter Falis -- which somehow causes them to switch bodies. Falis turns out to be a supreme fighter whatever body she's in, and at Alita's urging, she returns to the castle and puts down the coup. They have no way to switch back, so Falis-in-Alita's-body agrees to stick around until the prince returns to take over, while Alita-in-Falis's-body takes on the temporary identity of royal maidservant [[Milano Entolasia]]. Unfortunately, when the prince gets back, things only get worse...

Do Alita and Milano ever get unswapped? We'll never know -- the series ended too soon. All we know is that like most BEE TRAIN works, [[yuri]] fans love it.

title: lazflamme
body:
A [[mecha musume]] from the game [[cosmic break]], LazFlamme is characterized by her long, blond, ponytailed hair (although the normal version of her in-game sprite shows her with light blue hair); equine, centaur-like form; and an upper body armor that covers only the upper top part of her breasts.

She is the basic land unit players was able to get at the start of the game. However, in the current English version she have been replaced by [[Jikun Hu]]. She also had a [[chibi]] form. 

[[skj]] made a variant of her named [[centaur x]]. Its backstory is that the original Centaur X asked C.S. to turn him into a mecha musume.

Like other characters she does have other variations of herself, such as Lazflamme Duel(where she is covered entirely in armor, even her face) and Lazflamme rush.

Little is known about her in the present English version of Cosmic Break but she is often despicted with [[Lily_Rain]] and [[Crimrose]].

In-game description (normal):
[i] The "Blue Gale". Will kick anyone who stands behind her by reflex. You've been warned.[/i]

title: seraph_crimrose
body:
"[i]Crimrose obtained a new power through a strong desire to save her friend. She has now grown more powerful in order to continue fighting alongside that friend.[/i]"

A [[mecha musume]] from the game [[Cosmic Break]]. She is [[Crimrose]]'s alternate/"promotion" form first activated during her battle agaisnt [[Ivis]] while she was berserk, although the battle was only shown in the manga "Sacrifice". 

In-game she is obtainable by buying and using a "Seraph Promotion" or one of its many variants on a Crimrose that has reached level 8, 9 or 10. The higher her level is, the higher will be the Seraph's Capacity. It is impossible, for example, for a Crimrose that used "Seraph Promotion" at level 8 to reach the same Capacity of a Crimrose that used it at level 10.

title: lily_rain
body:
A [[mecha musume]] from the game [[cosmic break]], Lily Rain is characterized by her twintails and skirt-mounted weapon. She has three variants:

* Lily Rain, the 'standard' form players can get as their starting unit. Her skirt-mounted weapon is elongated and spear-like in shape, and her hair color is light blue. this 'standard' model also has a [[chibi]] form.
* Lily Rain Majalis, an alternate form obtainable in-game by gachapon-like premium service. Her hair is blonde and her skirt-mounted weapon is bell-shaped.
* Lily Rain EVE, a rare form only obtainable via limited-time gachapon. She wears a white dress, has light blue hair (but it's longer that the standard Lily Rain), and her weapon floats behind her instead of mounted on the waist.

title: gakkou_no_kaidan_(light_novel)
body:
Gakkō no Kaidan (学校の階段, lit. The School's Staircase) is a Japanese light novel series by Kaima Takaaki with illustrations by [[amafuku_amane|Amahuku Amane]]. The first novel in the series was released on January 30, 2006, and a total of twelve volumes have been published by Enterbrain under their Famitsu Bunko publishing imprint when the series concluded on July 30, 2009. A live action movie adaptation has premiered in Japanese theaters on June 9, 2007. It also has been adapted to a 4 volume manga illustrated by [[Yoshii Aki]]. The word kaidan used in the title is homophonic to the word kaidan (怪談), meaning "ghost stories".

title: borden
body:
Borden, Inc., was an American producer of food and beverage products, consumer products, and industrial products. At one time, the company was the largest U.S. producer of dairy and pasta products. Its food division, Borden Foods, was based in Columbus, Ohio, and focused primarily on pasta and pasta sauces, bakery products, snacks, processed cheese, jams and jellies, and ice cream. It was best known for its Borden Ice Cream, Meadow Gold milk, Creamette pasta, and Borden Condensed Milk brands. Its consumer products and industrial segment marketed wallpaper, adhesives, plastics and resins. By 1993, sales of food products accounted for 67 percent of its revenues. It was also known for its Elmer's Glue and Krazy Glue.

After significant financial losses in the early 1990s and a leveraged buyout by KKR in 1995, Borden divested itself of its various divisions, brands and businesses. KKR shuttered Borden's food products operations in 2001, and divested all its other Borden operations in 2005. The Borden dairy brands are currently used by both Dean Foods and Grupo Lala (as Borden Milk Products) for milk and by Dairy Farmers of America for cheese.

title: riderman
body:
Enemy, and later ally, of [[kamen_rider_v3|Kamen Rider V3]]. Also known as the "Avenging Demon".

A former scientist of the Destron organization framed as a traitor, Jouji Yuki takes up the name of Riderman to eliminate V3 and clear his name.

Riderman is not named the 4th Kamen Rider until [spoiler]he sacrifices himself to redirect a missile bound for Tokyo.[/spoiler]

His distinguishing features include his mechanical right arm and helmet that exposes the lower half of his face.

title: kamen_rider_x
body:
The fifth [[Kamen Rider]] and the protagonist of the franchise's third television series. Sometimes referred to as "X Rider."

After an attack on his father's laboratory orchestrated by the Government of Darkness, Keisuke Jin is surgically altered into Kamen Rider X and begins his campaign to end the organization's ambitions.

X is colored white with a red chest plate and accents. His design is based on a giant water bug, and thus is capable of operating underwater.

title: kamen_rider_hibiki
body:
Lead Rider of [[kamen_rider_hibiki_(series)|Kamen Rider Hibiki]], fifteenth show of the Kamen Rider series and sixth of the Heisei generation.

Hibiki is a veteran Oni Rider, having given up his humanity and his old name - Hidaka Hitoshi - to fight the Makamou, human-eating monsters who can only be defeated with the power of pure sound. When not fighting, Hibiki takes on his form when he was still Hitoshi.

Hibiki fights using [i]bachi[/i] sticks, which were used for [i]taiko[/i] drums. He can also upgrade into Hibiki Kurenai and finally Armed Hibiki.

title: kamen_rider_super-1
body:
The title [[Kamen Rider]] of the franchise's 7th installment.

Kazuya Oki aspires of going into outer space. To achieve his dream, he volunteers to undergo surgery to be made into an astronaut that can survive in space without the need of bulky space suits. The operation is a success and he is codenamed "Super-1".

The Dogma Kingdom attacks the launch base before Oki is sent up into space, leaving him as the sole survivor. Bent on avenging his colleagues, he returns to Japan to begin training that allows him to transform into Kamen Rider Super-1.

Super-1 is primarily colored silver and black, with a red scarf. His design is based on a hornet.
other_names: 仮面ライダースーパー1

title: kamen_rider_stronger
body:
Hero of the fifth [[Kamen Rider]] series.

Shigeru Jou volunteers to be made into one of Black Satan's cyborg soldiers, suspicious of their involvement in his friend's murder. With the operation complete, he escapes their headquarters taking a fellow altered human with him, [[electro_wave_human_tackle|Tackle]]. Together, they begin their campaign against evil.

Stronger has large green compound eyes and the letter "S" emblazoned on his chest. His design is based on the Japanese rhinoceros beetle.
other_names: 仮面ライダーストロンガー

title: kamen_rider_blade
body:
Lead Rider of [[kamen_rider_blade_(series)|Kamen Rider Blade]], fourteenth show of the Kamen Rider series and fifth of the Heisei generation.

Kenzaki Kazuma is an orphan whose zeal to protect the defenseless earned him a place in BOARD, a clandestine organization fighting the Undead, monsters who represent species vying for supreme reign over the world. Kenzaki was given the Rider System-02 - Blade - to help him fight off the Undead menace.

Blade has an indigo color scheme, and is patterned after the Hercules beetle ([i]dynastes hercules[/i]) and the Spades suit. He also has access to the winged Jack Form, as well as the powerful King Form.

title: kamen_rider_amazon
body:
The sole protagonist of the fourth television series in the [[Kamen Rider]] franchise.

Adopted by a local tribe after surviving a plane crash in the Amazon rainforest, he returns to Japan to take back a sacred armlet that had been stolen from his village.

A departure from his cyborg predecessors, Amazon resembles a combination of a giant lizard and possibly a piranha (people are still not sure). Despite his unique look, he still retains the traditional [[scarf]] and [[compound eyes]] of a Kamen Rider.

title: waltrud_krupinski
body:
Waltrud Krupinski (ヴァルトルート・クルピンスキー) is a veteran ace of the [[502nd Joint Fighter Wing]], originating from [[Karlsland]]. Her familiar is the Weimaraner.

Considered Karlsland's top veteran Ace, she joined the JG52 at around the same time as [[Gertrud Barkhorn]] and [[Erica Hartmann]], whom she considers good friends. She spent a good deal of time with Erica as her lead wingman. Among the 502nd JFW base, only Flight Lieutenant [[Gundula Rall]] has a higher confirmed kill count.

Tall, slender, and elegant, she has earned the nickname "Countess". She is also a hard-drinking womanizer and a hedonist with an easygoing personality. Despite her dauntless dog-fighting skill and sure marksmanship, her tendency to discard personal safety in favor of lining up for the attack rather than waiting means that she damages an unusually large number of Striker Unit, often making emergency landings under enemy fire.

Waltrud is based off Prussian-born German ace "Walter Krupinski":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Krupinski who, similar to Waltrud, was nicknamed Graf Pinski (Count Pinski) due to his Prussian origins.

2002: [[ikusa_megami_ii|Ikusa Megami 2 ~Ushinawareshi Kioku e no Chinkonka~]], direct sequel to the first game.
2008: [[ikusa_megami_zero|Ikusa Megami Zero]], prequel to the events of the entire series.
2010: [[ikusa_megami_verita|Ikusa Megami VERITA]], sequel to [[genrin_no_kishougun_2|Princess General 2]] and prequel to the first [[ikusa_megami|Battle Goddess]]
2014: [[tenbin_no_la_dea_~ikusa_megami_memoria~|Tenbin no La DEA. ~Ikusa Megami MEMORIA~]], a remake of the original [[ikusa_megami|Battle Goddess]], taking its place in the canon.
